      "title": "Summation of Infinite Series Using Limit as a Sum Principle",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Summation of Infinite Series Using Limit as a Sum Principle</strong></h3><p>If $f\\left( x \\right)$ is an integrable function defined on $\\left[ a,b \\right]$ then</p><p>$\\underset{h\\to 0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,[h\\{f\\left( a \\right)+f\\left( a+h \\right)+f\\left( a+2h \\right)+\\ldots +f(a+\\left( n-1 \\right)h\\}]$</p><p>is called the definite integral of $\\text{f}\\left( \\text{x} \\right)$ between limits $a$ and $\\text{b}$.</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\mathop{ \\int }_{a}^{b}f\\left( x \\right)dx=\\underset{h\\to 0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,h[\\{f\\left( a \\right)+f\\left( a+h \\right)+f\\left( a+2h \\right)+\\ldots +f(a+\\left( n-1 \\right)h\\}]$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"268\" height=\"184\">&nbsp;</p><p>$=\\underset{h\\to 0}{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\left| \\underset{r=0}{\\overset{n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,f\\left( a+rh \\right) \\right|$</p><p>It should be noted that as $\\text{b}\\to 0,\\text{a}\\to \\infty $</p><p>$\\text{nh}=\\text{b}-\\text{a}$</p><p>Putting $\\text{a}=0,\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ b}=1$, so that $\\text{h}=\\frac{1}{\\text{n}}$</p><p>We get $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\int _{0}^{t}f\\left( x \\right)dx=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\frac{1}{n}\\sum _{r=0}^{n-1}f\\left( \\frac{r}{n} \\right)$</p><p>WORKING RULE</p><p><strong>Step-1. </strong>Express the series in the form, $\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\left[ \\frac{1}{n}\\sum f\\left( \\frac{r}{n} \\right) \\right]$</p><p><strong>Step-2. </strong>Replace $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\sum $ by $\\int $,</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{r}}{\\text{n}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ by }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ x }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$</p><p>$\\left( \\frac{1}{n} \\right)\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ by }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ dx}$</p><p><strong>Step-3. </strong>Obtain the lower &amp; upper limits of the integral by computing $\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\left( \\frac{r}{n} \\right)$ for the least &amp; greatest value of $\\text{r}$ respectively i.e. put the starting &amp; ending values of $\\text{r}$ to get the limits.</p><p><strong>Illustration&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Show that </strong>$\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\left( \\frac{1}{n+1}+\\frac{1}{n+2}+\\frac{1}{n+3}+\\ldots +\\frac{1}{6n} \\right)=\\text{log}6$</p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}}<br>{} &amp; \\left. \\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\left( \\frac{1}{n+1}+ \\right.\\frac{1}{n+2}+\\frac{1}{n+3}+\\ldots +\\frac{1}{6n} \\right) \\\\<br>{} &amp; ~=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\left( \\frac{1}{n+1}+\\frac{1}{n+2}+\\frac{1}{n+3}+\\ldots +\\frac{1}{n+5n} \\right) \\\\<br>\\end{array}$</p><p>[writing last term in the same form as the 1st, 2nd, $3rd,..$. terms are]</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}}<br>{} &amp; ~=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\underset{r=1}{\\overset{5n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,\\frac{1}{n+r}=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\underset{r=1}{\\overset{5n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,\\frac{1}{n}\\left( \\frac{n}{n+r} \\right) \\\\<br>{} &amp; ~=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\frac{1}{n}\\underset{r=1}{\\overset{5n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,\\frac{1}{1+\\frac{r}{n}} \\\\<br>\\end{array}$</p><p>$\\because \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ lower limit of $\\text{r}=1$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ lower limit of integration $=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\left( \\frac{1}{n} \\right)=0$</p><p>$\\because \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ upper limit of $r=5n$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ upper limit of integration $=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\frac{5n}{n}=5$</p><p>Hence from (i) required limit</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}}<br>=\\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{5}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{1+\\text{x}}=[\\text{log}\\left( 1+\\text{x} \\right)]_{0}^{5} &amp; {} \\\\<br>=\\text{log}6-\\text{log}1=\\text{log}6 &amp; \\left[ \\because \\text{log}1=1 \\right] \\\\<br>\\end{array}$</p><p><strong>Illustration&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Evaluate $\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\left( \\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{1}^{2}}}+\\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{2}^{2}}}+\\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{3}^{2}}}+\\ldots +\\frac{1}{2n} \\right)$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution : $\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\left( \\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{1}^{2}}}+\\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{2}^{2}}}+\\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{3}^{2}}}+\\ldots +\\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{n}^{2}}} \\right)$&nbsp;</strong></p><p>[Writing last term in the same form as first, $2\\text{nd},3\\text{rd},\\ldots .$. term are]</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}}<br>{} &amp; ~=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\underset{r=1}{\\overset{n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,\\left( \\frac{n}{{{n}^{2}}+{{r}^{2}}} \\right)=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\frac{1}{n}\\underset{r=1}{\\overset{n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,\\frac{{{n}^{2}}}{{{n}^{2}}+{{r}^{2}}} \\\\<br>{} &amp; ~=\\underset{n\\to \\infty }{\\mathop{\\text{lim}}}\\,\\frac{1}{n}\\underset{r=1}{\\overset{n}{\\mathop \\sum }}\\,\\frac{1}{1+{{\\left( \\frac{r}{n} \\right)}^{2}}} ...(i) \\\\<br>\\end{array}$</p><p>$\\because \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ lower limit of $\\text{r}=1$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ lower limit of integration $=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\frac{1}{n}=0$</p><p>$\\because \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ upper limit of $\\text{r}=\\text{n}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ upper limit of integration $=\\text{li}{{\\text{m}}_{n\\to \\infty }}\\frac{n}{n}=1$</p><p>Hence from (i), required limit</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}}<br>{} &amp; ~=\\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{1}\\frac{\\text{dx}}{1+{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}=\\left[ \\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\text{x} \\right]_{0}^{1} \\\\<br>{} &amp; ~=\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( 1 \\right)-\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( 0 \\right) \\\\<br>{} &amp; ~=\\frac{\\pi }{4}-0=\\frac{\\pi }{4} \\\\<br>\\end{array}$</p>",
